efforts of many gallant officers, who lavi&s;hly ex|po&s;ed,
and even lo&s;t their lives in the honourable di&s;charge
of their duty<NOTE N="&ast;" PLACE="foot"><P>The following anecdote is &s;o remarkable, and tends &s;o much to the honour of the Briti&s;h &s;oldiery, that we in&s;ert it without &s;eat of the reader's di&s;approbation:&mdash;Captain Och$erlony and En&s;ign Peyton belonged to the regiment of Brigadier-General Monckton. They were nearly of an age, which did not exceed thirty; the fir&s;t was a North-Briton, the other a $word$ of Ireland. Both were agreeable in per&s;on, and unblemi&s;hed in chara$$$ and connected together by the ties of mutual friend&s;hip and e&s;teem. On the day that preceded the battle, Captain Ochterlony had been obliged to $span$ duel with a German officer; in which, though he wounded and $span$ antagoni&s;t, yet he him&s;elf received a dangerous hurt under the right $word$ con&s;equence of which his friends in&s;i&s;ted on his remaining in camp $word$ the action of next day; but his &s;pirit was too great to comply with $$$$ mon&s;trance. He declared it &s;hould never be &s;aid that a &s;cratch received $word$ private rencounter had prevented him from doing his duty, when his coun$$$ required his &s;ervice; and he took the field with a fu&s;il in his hand, though he was hardly able to carry his arms. In leading up his men to the $word$ entrenchment, he was &s;hot through the lungs with a mu&s;quet-ball, an $$$ dent which obliged him to part with his fu&s;il: but he &s;till continued a$|vancing, until, by lo&s;s of blood, he became too weak to proceed farther. About the &s;ame time Mr. Peyton was lamed by a &s;hot, which &s;hattered the &s;mall bone of his left leg. The &s;oldiers, in their retreat, earne&s;tly begged, with tears in their eyes, that Captain Ochterlony would allow them to $word$ him and the en&s;ign o$$ the field. But he was &s;o bigotted to a &s;evere point $word$ honour, that he would not quit the ground, though he de&s;ired they would take care of his en&s;ign. Mr. Peyton, with a generous di&s;dain, rejected their good o$fice$