<P>Captain Ochterlony &s;at down by his friend, and, as they expected nothing but immediate death, they took leave of each other; yet they were not alto$gether abandoned by the hope of being protected as pri&s;oners: for the capt$$ &s;eeing a French &s;oldier with two Indians approach, &s;tarted up, and $span$ them in the French language, which he &s;poke perfectly well, expre&s;&s;ed $word$ expectation that they would treat him and his companion as officers, pri&s;oner, and gentlemen. The two Indians &s;eemed to be entirely under the $word$ of the Frenchman, who coming up to Mr. Peyton, as he &s;at on the $word$ &s;natched his $aced hat from his head, and robbed the captain of his $span$ money. This outrage was a &s;ignal to the Indians for murther and $word$ One of them, clubbing his firelock, &s;truck at him behind, with a view to knock him down, but the blow mi&s;&s;ing his head, took place upon $span$ At the &s;ame in&s;tant the other Indian po$red his &s;hot$ into the $span$ unfortunate young gentleman, who cried out, &startq;O Peyton! the $span$ &s;hot me.&endq; Not yet &s;atiated with cruelty, the barbarian &s;prung upon $word$ and &s;tabbed him in the belly with his &s;calping knife. The captain, $word$ pa$$ed with his fu&s;i, had no weapon for his defence, as none of the $word$ wore &s;words in the action. The three $ru&s;&s;ians, finding him &s;till alive, $word$ deavoured to &s;trangle him with his own $word$; and he was now upon his $word$ &s;truggling again&s;t them with &s;urpri&s;ing exertion. Mr. Peyton, at $word$ juncture, having a double barrelled mu$quet in his hand, and &s;eeing the $word$ of his friend, fired at one of the Indians, who dropped dead upon the $word$. The other, thinking the en&s;ign would now be an ea&s;y prey, advanced towards him, and Mr. Peyton, having taken good aim at the di&s;tance of four yards, di&s;charged his piece the &s;econd time, but it &s;eemed to take no effect. The &s;avage fired in his turn, and wounded the en&s